{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:07:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17781"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17781"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.1,0.05,0,0.85]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82571"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67736"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8517"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24561"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82571"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stratum corneum is the outermost layer of the epidermis and serves as the primary barrier between the body and the environment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the composition of the stratum corneum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Living Langerhans cells in keratin","Living keratinocytes filled with melanin","Living fibroblasts embedded in collagen","Dead melanocytes in a lipid matrix","Dead keratinocytes filled with keratin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stratum corneum consists of \u003Cstrong\u003Edead keratinocytes filled with keratin\u003C/strong\u003E, which are flattened cells called corneocytes. These cells form multiple layers surrounded by specialised lipids, creating a robust protective barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding why the other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiving Langerhans cells in keratin\u003C/strong\u003E are antigen-presenting immune cells found in deeper epidermal layers, not in the stratum corneum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiving keratinocytes filled with melanin\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because stratum corneum cells are dead, and melanin production occurs in melanocytes, not keratinocytes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiving fibroblasts embedded in collagen\u003C/strong\u003E describes components of the dermis, not the stratum corneum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDead melanocytes in a lipid matrix\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as melanocytes reside in the basal layer of the epidermis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe unique arrangement of corneocytes connected by corneodesmosomes and surrounded by lipids creates an effective barrier against water loss and environmental insults.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The stratum corneum consists of dead keratinocytes filled with keratin protein that form a protective barrier.","The stratum corneum is composed of 15-20 layers of flattened, anucleate corneocytes embedded in a lipid matrix.","The main function of the stratum corneum is to prevent water loss and protect against environmental damage."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67736"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17781"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67736"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-29T23:21:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-29T23:22:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10495"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82571"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Skin and Associated Structures","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt